The federal government has kicked off the distribution of Coronavirus palliatives to the vulnerable people across the state. Performing the ceremony in Gusau, Zamfara State capital, the minister of Humanitarian, Disaster Management and Social Development, Hajia Sadiya Umar Faruk, said the palliatives would cover old people and the physically challenged. Giving the breakdown of food items available for distribution, she said 49 trailers of Maize, 47 Trailers of Sorghum, and eight trailers of millet will be given to over 61000 households in the state. Faruk, however, reiterated the concern of President Muhammadu Buhari over the act of banditry in the state and other parts of the country. The minister also said 29,800 bags of 50kg fertilizer were already supplied to store for distribution to farmers. According to her, the act of banditry has ravaged the state, with the loss of lives and properties, hence federal government’s intervention, especially with the effect of Coronavirus pandemic worsening the situation of people in the state. The minister added that over 130,000 would benefit from the federal government cash transfer programme. In his speech, Governor Bello Mohammed Matawalle lauded the federal government for the distribution of palliatives in the state, and added that his administration has also introduced Zamfara Social Intervention Programme to support less privileged persons.